document.originaltext: After the yajamāna has performed the nityakṛya, a mātṛpūjā and an ābhyudayika, and after he has fed the Brahmins, he starts on the decorated ground in the maṇḍapa the kuśakāṇḍikā. He sweeps the place for the sacrificial fire with kuśa and throws it away in the northeastern direction. He besmears the place for the sacrificial fire with cow dung and water. He scratches the place for the sacrificial fire three times with the lower part of sruva as long as one prādeśa. Using thumb and ringfinger he takes out the earth in the order of scratching. He besprinkles the place for the sacrificial fire with water. He brings the fire in a kāṁsyapātra and, having turned the face westward, places it. West of the fire and south of the yajamāna the mother, who has bathed and is wearing mahatavāsaḥ, takes the boy on her lap and sits down. Now the saṁkalpa is made. The patron selects the Brahmin by the adyakṛtavya tvam ahaṁ vṛṇe, who answers with the om vṛtosmi. The patron says the yathā vihitaṁ karma kuru and gets as answer the karavāṇi. Then the patron provides a āsana south of the fire, on which he strews kuśa having the tips turned eastward. He makes the priest to circumambulate the fire in clockwise direction and addresses him with the asmin karmaṇi tvaṁ me brahmā bhava. The priest says the bhavani and having the face turned toward the north he sits down there on the seat prepared for him. He fills a prāṇītapātrā with water, covers it with kuśa, looks at the face of the Brahman and puts it north of the fire on kuśa. He places in each case the fourth part of the barhis from the southeast to the northeast the tips facing toward the north, from the brahman to the fire the tip facing toward the east, from the southwest to the northwest the tip facing toward the north and from the fire to the prāṇītapātrā. North of the fire in western direction he deposits following items from east to west: three kuśa for cutting the pavitra, two kuśa with intact tips for making the purifier, the prokṣāṇīpātra, the ājyasthālī, kuśa for sammārjana, upayamanakuśa, three samidh, the sruva, ājya, and the pūrṇapātra filled with 256 handful of taṇḍula. North of these general items, he fetches śitodaka, uṣṇodaka, a piṇḍa of ghṛta, dadhi and navanīta, a śallīkaṇṭa with three white spots, 27 kuśa with tips having the length of a prādeśa, an tāmrapariṣkṛtalohakṣura, the nāpita, a vṛdabhagomayapiṇḍa and other items like according to custom a nalinīdala. Then, having cut the pavitra with the pavitracedanakuśa, he gives three times with hand and pavitra praṇītodaka into the prokṣaṇīpātra. He seizes the pavitra, whose tip is turned toward the north, with ringfinger and thumb and performs three utpavana. For this he takes the pavitracedanakuśa in the left hand, and three times sprinkles the prokṣaṇījala upwards. He consecrates the prokṣaṇī with the praṇītodaka and consecrates with the prokṣaṇījala the deposited utensils. He places the prokṣaṇīpātra in the middle between the fire and the praṇītā. He puts ājya in the ājyapātra and heats it up. He takes a burning tṛṇa, turns it clockwise above the vessel and throws it into the fire. Then he three times warms the sruva and sweeps it with the sammārjanakuśa, with the tip of the grass from the inner side and with the roots of the grass from the outer side. He besprinkles the sruva with the praṇītodaka. As before he three times warms the sruva and puts it down to the southern side. Then he turns the ājya in clockwise direction around the fire and places it in front of himself. Then he three times purifies it with the prokṣaṇī, looks for bad things fallen into it and removes them, and as before purifies the ājya with the prokṣaṇī. Then he stands up, takes the upayamanakuśa in the left hand, meditates in mind about the God Prajāpati, seizes silently three samidh and throws them into the fire. Then he sits down, sprinkles with the pavitra the prokṣaṇyodaka in clockwise direction around the fire and puts the purifiersinto the praṇītāpātra. Being touched by the brahman and having the right knee bent he offers in the kindled fire. After every offering he casts the ghee remaining on the sruva into the prokṣaṇīpātra. the āghārājyahoma with the om prajāpataye svāhā idaṁ, prajāpataye spoken only mentally to Prajāpati and with the om indrāya etc. to Indra, the ājyabhāgau with the agnaye etc. to Agni and with the somāya etc. to Soma, the mahāvyāhṛtihoma with the om bhūḥ svāhā, idam agnaye , with the om bhuvaḥ svāhā, idaṁ vāyave to and with the oṁ svaḥ svāhā idaṁ sūryāya to , the pañcavāruṇīhoma with the om tvanno agne etc. to Agni and Vāruṇa, with the om satvanno etc. to Agni and Vāruṇa, with the om ayāścāgna etc. to Agni, with the om yeteśatam etc. to Vāruṇa, Savitṛ, Viṣṇu, the Viśvedevas, the Maruts and the Svarkas and with the uduttamaṁ etc. to Vāruṇa, the prajāpatyahoma with the om prajāpataye svāhā etc. to Prajāpati and the agnisviṣṭakṛddhoma with the om agnaye sviṣṭakṛte etc. to Agni Sviṣṭakṛt. Then he eats the remains, sips water, sweeps the mouth with the pavitra and throws the pavitra into the fire. He takes the pūrṇāpātra and, after speaking the amukanāmna kumārasya cūḍākaraṇāṅgahomkarmāṇi etc., hands it over. The Brahman accepts it and says the om svasti. While saying the om sumitriyā etc. he sweeps the head with the pavitra. In the northeast he turns the praṇītāpātra upside down with the om durmitriyā etc.. Then he raises the barhis in the before mentioned order offers it by the hand with the om deva gatu etc. into the fire. He the father mixes warm water into cold water with the om uṣṇenavāya udakena etc.. He silently puts navanīta, gh.rta and dadhi into the mixed water. He moistens the godāna on the southern side with the mixed water and speaks the om savitrāprasūtādaiyā etc.. He silently unravels the hair with a porcupine's quill that has three white spots. He takes three of 27 blades of a kuśa prepared before and places them in the hair with the tips of the blades showing to the root of the hair. He speaks the om auṣadhe etc.. He takes the razor with the om śivonāmāsi etc.. With the om nirvartayāmi etc. he brings the iron razor into contact with the kuśa and hair. He seizes the separated hair and the kuśa blades and cuts it with the om yenāvapat etc.. North of the fire the sister if available throws hair and grass on a kāṁsyapātra on which a lump of dung of a bull is placed. He silently moistens the hair on the southern side again. He silently separates it with the porcupine quill. He silently places three kuśa blades in the hair. He silently brings the razor into contact with hair and kuśa. Hair and kuśa are silently thrown on the lump of bull's dung. Who has touched the cut hair needs to touch water. The moistening with water, the placing of kuśa in the hair, the connecting with the razor and the throwing on bull's dung are silently performed a third time. He moistens the tuft on the western side with the mixed water and speaks the savitrāprasūtādaiyā etc.. He silently unravels the hair with a porcupine's quill. He takes three blades of kuśa and places them in the hair. He speaks the om auṣadhe etc.. He takes the razor with the om śivonāmāsi etc.. With the om nirvartayāmi etc. he brings the razor into contact with kuśa and hair. He seizes the separated hair and the kuśa blades and cuts it with the om yenāvapat etc.. Hair and kuśa are thrown on the dung of a bull. After touching the cut hair water shall be touched. He silently moistens the hair on the western side again. He silently separates it with the porcupine quill. He silently places three kuśa blades in the hair. He silently brings the razor into contact with hair and kuśa. Hair and kuśa are silently thrown on the lump of bull's dung. Who has touched the cut hair needs to touch water. The moistening with water, the placing of kuśa in the hair, the connecting with the razor and the throwing on bull's dung are silently performed a third time. He moistens the tuft on the eastern side with water and speaks the om savitrāprasūtādaiyā etc.. He silently unravels the hair with a porcupine's quill. He takes three blades of kuśa and places them in the hair. He speaks the om auṣadhe etc.. He takes the razor with the om śivonāmāsi etc.. With the om nirvartayāmi etc. he brings the razor into contact with kuśa and hair. He seizes the separated hair and the kuśa blades and cuts it with the om yenāvapat etc.. Hair and kuśa are thrown on the dung of a bull. He silently moistens the hair on the eastern side again. He silently separates it with the porcupine quill. He silently places three kuśa blades in the hair. He silently brings the razor into contact with hair and kuśa. Hair and kuśa are silently throws on the lump of bull's dung. Water is touched. The moistening with water, the placing of kuśa in the hair, the connecting with the razor and the throwing on bull's dung are silently performed a third time. Starting from the right ear and ending at the right ear he turns the razor in clockwise direction around the head of the boy, the first time with the om yat kṣureṇa etc., the second and third time silently. The whole head of the boy is moistened. Then he gives the razor to the barber with the om akṣaṇvan parivapa. The boy is facing east or north. The barber keeps one śikhā and shaves the rest of head of the boy completely. According to custom the mother puts the hairs in a new cloth and gives a portion of curd and milk on the lump of cow dung. Then the father hides hair and cow dung by enwrapping it with cloth and he or a representative deposits it on a waterside. Then the father worships a prepared varadravya, takes it and, after speaking the amukanāmna kumārasya cūḍākaraṇakarmāḍgatayā etc., gives it to the svācārya. The father stands up and casts with the om mūrdhānam etc. ghṛta over fruit and cloth placed on the sruva. After having declared the saṁkalpa to feed the Brahmins, he sits down and fetches with the sruva some ashes and makes with ashes taken by be tip of the right ringfinger the tryāyuṣa, , with the om tryāyuṣañjamadagneḥ the forehead, with the kaśyapasya tryāyuṣam the neck, with the om yadeveśu tryāyuṣam the upper part of the right arm and with the om tanno astu tryāyuṣa the heart. In the same order he marks the forehead etc. of the boy, but here the om tanno astu etc. is recited instead of the om tanno astu etc.. Then the priest gives dūrva, akṣata and so forth and performs the āśīrmantrapātha. Then that hair, which is placed on the lump of cow's dung, is thrown away in cow stall, at a river or at another water side. After having satisfied the Brahmans with bhojana etc. he himself eats together with friends.
